There’s only 1 major difference between these two pictures: 

I stopped training for aesthetics and I started training for PERFORMANCE. 

Don’t get me wrong, I worked hard as FUCK in both

& believe it or not I was in a growing phase in both… but.. 

On the left I was getting in my own goddamn way. I would walk into the gym with the goal of ReMaINinG AEsTHetiC, do the same 10-12 rep range workout for hypertrophy, and eat to remain decently lean. 

On the right I walk into the gym and say FUCK what I look like I’m here to PERFORM. I walk in with a weight or rep PR attempt in mind according to my program, I fuel myself to perform better (not look better) and I celebrate my body for what it can DO and not what it LOOKS LIKE. 

It’s empowering as fuck. 

& the funny things is that by not training for aesthetics… I actually look more aesthetic now…. 🤣

Which makes sense bc you HAVE to give your muscle fibers an adequate stimulus to JUSTIFY diverting energy (a precious resource to your body, biologically speaking) to adding muscle tissue. That means push it to lift heavier. Week after week. 

So moral of the story: 

Stop training for how you look and start training for how you train. 

& aim to TRAIN BETTER week after week. And only then will you actually look better week after week. 

I might be biased but I truly have never done a better workout focused on performance than my gluteguides and there’s a reason I advocate for them so much. 

The guides are performance based. NOT aesthetic based. 

And the result of that is… Well I’d say they speak for themselves :)

This is off-season. 

it’s taken me a while to get here but here’s what I’ve learned off-season is NOT:
- a time to train less hard
- a time to chase your goals with any less vigor 
- a time to track every single thing to the gram 
- a time to say no to EVERY social opportunity 
- a time to continue to put non-fitness goals on the back burner 
- a time to eat anything you want whenever you want just because you’re not on prep 

Off-season, atleast for me, has evolved into something so fucking beautiful: 

I still make sure my workouts are being prioritized and my training intensity is ON one.

I still track the majority of my meals, even on vacay, opting for my own trackable options WHEN it’s the MORE DESIRABLE food
option for me. 

I still have meals out, track food at restaurants, and try new Foreign delicacies, having untracked meals and days when it makes more sense. 

I still have to sacrifice some things in the name of my goals, but with a new flexibility that makes that sacrifice occur less often and less against my will. 

All in all, it really took 5 months post show and a major surgery forcing me away from the gym to improve my relationship w food and w training but now that I’m on the other side of it, I FEEL SO FUCKING GOOD. 

if you don’t compete, take this as a rough outline of what I hope my non-competing fitness journey continues to look like. 

It’s not 100% fitness nor 100% flexibility, but it has just enough discipline to fulfill me and to keep my on my No Pussy Shit 😌

Yes there are people with better physiques than you—probably with less effort too—because of their genetics. 

And yeah, this probably frustrates you as you swipe on the gram longing for what they have. 

I know I used to feel powerless knowing how hard I had to work for what others seemed to get so easily. 

But have you ever considered that there’s also people out there naturally better at math than you? Or at painting? Or at tap dancing? 

You probably don’t sit around under-appreciating your own attributes because you’re too busy sulking over the mathematicians of the world right? 

So why do you do that over those genetically gifted in the physique department? 

Because you cultivated an environment (your instagram) that allows you to do so. 

I’m not saying never look up to anyone’s physique— if you wanna be great at training or great at body building you should most DEFINITELY have people you can look up to. 

As with any endeavor, experts in any field can be an incredible resource. 

BUT the same way you would learn math from a math TEACHER and not just by watching a mathematician ~math~, make sure you’re adequately cultivating en environment that can facilitate your growth too. 

Look up to people who teach you and motivate you and inspire you. 

Or else you’re just setting yourself up for feelings of inadequacy.

YOUR ENVIRONMENT SHOULD FACILITATE YOUR GROWTH.

“No pussy shit” 

Yes it means go harder in the gym. And yes it means do the Hard Things. But it isn’t only about what you DO. It’s also about what you EXPECT of yourself. And the standard you hold yourself to. 

Expectations come in various forms: as goals & standards ofcourse but also as the environment you put yourself in and in the people you surround yourself by. 

So often we convince ourselves we’re doing Hard Things or giving our all, but really it’s just because we put ourselves in an environment that’s so comparatively dull, that we automatically shine in it. We choose environments and people that are comfortable and make us feel good. So that we can justify staying in the same place.

That’s literally fucking pussy shit. 

If you only feel content about what you do and how you perform because you curated an environment or you surround yourself with people who make you feel accomplished by doing the bare minimum….. that’s pussy shit. 

Elevate your expectations for yourself. EVEN if it makes you feel behind for a little bit. Or it makes you feel scared. Or it challenges you. 

You can only ever elevate yourself if you set the expectation that you will. 

So surround yourself by people who push you—not by people who constantly convince you it’s okay to stay exactly where you are. 

Put yourself in an environment that pushes you— not somewhere that is comfortable enough to stay exactly where you are. 

Push yourself to push yourself—hold yourself to a standard that forces you to evolve from exactly where you are. 

THATS what No Pussy Shit means. It means admitting you can be more and do more and then demanding that of yourself. 

.

100lbs vs 124lbs. 

Your dream physique weighs more than you think. I’ve said it before but I’ll gladly say it again and again. 

If you think this was easy for me to come to terms with you’re TRIPPIN. 

“I don’t wanna gain weight” yeah homie I didn’t think I wanted to either and then I gained 20+ lbs 🤣

And while I’m more COMFORTABLE in the left (because I have less adiposity), if I fought to stay that way I would’ve always stayed that way. No change, no growth. 

Instead I got uncomfortable. And I’m STILL uncomfortable. It’s an everyday mental battle to come to terms with a new ~bigger and ~heavier physique. 

But looking back, I’m so happy I kept going past the discomfort. Bc it allowed me to GROW. 

And you know what if you prefer staying leaner, that’s OKAY!!! (I do too!!) BUT imagine how much better you’ll look next time you’re lean if you take a phase to GROW. Like…… mmYA. 

Take it from me, whether you wanna be bigger or you wanna stay lean, a growing phase is ALWAYS in your best interest.

I’ve been struggling for the majority of the year. I had such high hopes for 2023 when it started but to be completely honest, the first few months were some of the darkest days I’ve experienced mentally. From being away from the gym during recovery, to dealing with body image and not recognizing my body because of weight gain + new implants, confronting pain from my previous relationship that I thought I could avoid, to feeling a lack of purpose and direction without prep, there were some VERY dark days. 

When Erin and I planned Cabo, I knew I owed it to myself to make a change in the way I was behaving and the way I was feeling. I knew above ALL, this trip was something I wanted to look back on with nothing but joy in my heart and I knew that would only happen if I was able to get out of my own way and let myself be PRESENT while there. 

So when I started my Cabo cut it was NOT about a weight goal or a physique goal — it was about getting to a mental place where I felt GOOD in my skin and GOOD about my actions. A mental place where I felt fulfilled and proud of my work and where I could be present in the moment without mentally being in my own way. 

And in reflecting on everything: I did just that. And I feel DAMN GOOD. 

During this trip I was mentally so present and in tune with myself, with my surroundings, with my body, my mind, and everything in between. 

So when you see me joking about Cabo Val or see me posting a side of me you don’t usually see, know that there is so much more behind every single one of those pictures and every single one of those smiles. 

Cabo Val represents a version of me that overcame SO many mental demons, fears, insecurities, feelings of inadequacy, etc. and was able to have the literal best week of my life. 

There are a lot of versions of val and we love them all but Cabo Val has a special place in my heart 🥂💘

YOU CAN HAVE BOTH!!!!

elite physiques require elite effort to create and maintain. 

it’s truly that simple. 

I feel like lately (ever since the move/ surgery/ switch to intuitive eating) I’ve fallen into a mental place of trying so hard to find this “balance” in my life… and what I did instead was decrease my overall effort and increase my overall leniency and called it balance. 

And as a result, my physique has reflected these changes. 

I see people living “effortlessly” and trick myself into thinking I’ll magically ease into my dream physique with decreased effort because “balance”!! 

Fuck. That. 

I’ve learned the hard way that there is a direct positive correlation between my physique and my effort — no matter the goal. And I’ve also learned the hard way that intuitive eating does NOT REQUIRE ANY LESS EFFORT THAN TRACKING if you still want to create / maintain an elite physique. 

I realized there was a disconnect between the version of myself I want to be and the person I was acting like. 

The only way to be the best version of me is to simply BE THE BEST VERSION OF ME. 

There’s no waiting there’s no wishing there’s no hoping.

There’s just working. 

So here’s to a month of doing the Hard Things. Of leaving excuses behind. Of aligning our DAILY actions with the person we want to become. 

You get out what you put in. So put in everything you’ve got. 

&&& while you’re busy becoming the next version of you, don’t forget to look back and see just how far you’ve come. It’ll only push you to keep going.

I think modern interpretations of ‘self love’ are bullsh*t 

as a society we talk so much about self love, self acceptance, etc. and all too often I think that comes accompanied with complacency of a state you’re not TRULY content with. 

self love does not mean loving yourself as you are that you never have to change… 

self love is loving yourself enough as you are TO put in the effort to change when it would serve you more. it’s recognizing that you, right now, ARE worthy of your effort. worthy of everything it takes to become the dream version of yourself. 

you have to see the value in something before you commit to investing in it. THAT to me is what self love is. recognizing your value, your worth —right now as you are — and realizing you are worth the investment. 

sometimes (most of the times imo) changing & improving yourself is an act of love, not of hate. 

so love yourself enough to put in the effort to become anything and everything you’ve ever dreamed of. I promise you’re worth it. 

recognizing the need for change won’t be easy, and when you do and put in the effort that won’t be easy either but hey..

I know you’re giving it your ALL. and yet you feel like you’re getting nowhere. And you think the answer is to just work harder. you might be wrong. 

your environment is just as important as your effort. 

I blew my own mind when I realized this: 

Your environment can and will determine how much you get out of your effort. 

Think about someone doing an ALL OUT sprint, exerting 100% maximal effort.

Now place them on an escalator… that’s going down. They’re giving their absolute all but the escalator is working against them, and as a result they’re staying in the same place. 

Now take that same person, same sprint, same 100% effort… pick them up and place them on an escalator going UP.

& watch them take tf off. 

In both scenarios the effort, the work, the will, the want were the same. But in one situation the environment was holding them back, and in the other it was propelling them forward.

I see this all the time. I see people putting in hard fucking work. Getting everything done. Executing to a T. And yet they feel like they’re not progressing. 

but they’re stuck in a job that doesn’t respect them, in a relationship that drains them, in friendships that guilt them, in a town that holds them back. 

YOUR ENVIRONMENT IS CRUCIAL TO FACILITATING YOUR SUCCESS. 

& it includes everything from when you wake up, the weather, food availability, gym culture, friendships, family, partners, hobbies, living space, job, etc. 

cultivate an environment that propels you, that AUGMENTS what you reap from your effort. 

It’s not easy to make the structural changes needed to create that,but you’re worth more than settling for easy. You’re worth more than living your entire life exerting yourself on a backwards escalator. 

So get Tf over it and do the Hard Things.

this one’s for all my girls (and guys) who are attached to some arbitrary number on the scale. let. It. go. 

YOUR DREAM PHYSIQUE WEIGHS MORE THAN YOU THINK. 

it’s about making sure that everyday you are fulfilling the actions you know you need to do to get where you wanna be. 

it’s about sticking to your nutritional protocol (and making sure it’s adequately aligned with your goals) ((aka make sure you’re eating ENOUGH or hire someone to do that for you))

it’s about training with INTENTION and progressively overloading (making sure you’re feeling EVERY rep and forcing yourself to engage the weight better each session to push yourself harder whether that be adding weight, adding reps, slowing down the tempo, etc)

it’s about executing the nonnegotiables with intention (how are you sleeping, recovering, resting, spending your energy, fueling your thoughts, etc) 

And it’s about consistency. about showing up day in and day out—even in the absence of results. it’s about sticking to the protocol even if the scale jumps up or jumps down. It’s about not quickly reacting. It’s about not letting temporary emotions derail the objective tasks at hand for long term goals. It’s about not giving in to instant gratification. 

Food + proper training + nonnegotiables + consistent effort day in and day out = results. 

Simple math really 🤓

Kicking off this year with a word vomit, naturally, of my first few thoughts as a 24 year old: 

Ive been reflecting ALOT on what I accomplished while I was 23… and to be honest it took me a lot of digging to feel proud. When I turned 23 I was in a different place and most of the goals I set for myself were social media-growth related. I thought I wanted to go all in on this. So when I’m looking back and I see less followers instead of more, those stupid numbers make me feel like I failed. And it’s so fkn dumb that I let silly little numbers on a screen take away from everything I’ve accomplished in REAL life. I GOT INTO my dream grad program and accepted an opportunity to TEACH & facilitate a graduate class (???!?? More info soon hehe), I moved myself across the country, flew my mom out, live in my DREAM apt, grew my coaching business and have helped more women than ever, gave myself not one but TWO b00b jobs (🤣), went on the best trip of my life, strengthened all my friendships, dug myself out of a dark place after my first surgery, have grown more internally than ever before, live in a new city with an amazing new environment, and now have been working on the next big project… all on my own dime at 23 mf years old!!!!! Yet somehow. Those dumb numbers on a screen make me forget all that….. 

respectfully, F*CK THAT 🤣

As I grew this year, I realized that I didn’t want my life to be 100% social media and I put more energy into my real offline life instead. So I didn’t meet any of my goals. & that’s OKAY. I’ve accepted that THIS is what these years are for. For learning what you want out of life and what you don’t, experimenting with jobs & places & people, and keeping what works and getting rid of what doesn’t. 

I love sharing my life but I also love putting the work into my offline life! 

So 24 is about just that. It’s simply about real life. About becoming the person I’ve dreamed of being. About acting like her day in and day out. And about VALidating myself with what I do in my real life and not with numbers on a screen.

That is all!!! Thank you for joining today’s alphamine + journal session 🤪 here’s to twenty f*cking four!!!!

When you grow up overweight (swipe), you develop a deep rooted aversion and fear to the concept of weight gain.

My body has never struggled putting on weight, especially body fat. So I’ve spent most of my life fighting my physiology and trying to be the smallest possible version of myself. I know, at least for me, when I first lost weight (I previously had high cholesterol and other unhealthy biomarkers so even though I was young, it was necessary for my health) I celebrated my weight loss and was praised for it. Rightfully so bc I fkn did that! But what I didn’t know was the subconscious fears I was establishing. 

Fears of being the “chubby friend” again 
Fears of carbs lol 
Fears of striving for anything other than weight loss 

When I look at my goals of becoming a Pro, I know I need to bigger. I know I need to grow. 

But there’s a voice in the back of my head that carries all the trauma from my overweight past that makes the process of gaining weight and growing SO mentally hard. I have to remind myself every day that even though I once underwent a big weight loss, I am NOT that person anymore. And it’s OKAY to grow. It’s OKAY to do what serves me NOW. 

I post a ton of weight gain transformations and I talk about them being hard but y’all let me tell you it’s HARD! there’s a part of me that carries these fears of weight gain and I have to wake up and shut her up everyday!!!

But I do it and I keep on keeping on and when I stop look back at my progress I can see that it was worth it. 

So if you’re in a similar boat, please remember: it won’t be easy but we can do hard things 💘

mmmm as a full-time grad student, researcher, coach, bodybuilder, and (I guess) full-time iNfLuEnCer (cringe) I wanna talk about ✨burnout✨ 

y’all had lots of questions about dealing with (or rather avoiding) burnout when you have a lot on your plate. so here are my BIGGEST tips:

1. Journal every morning so you can get your mindset right AND plan out how to balance your daily demands. the days will be busy! Journalling helps you get a Birds Eye view for the day ahead AND it allows you to think through & anticipate any roadblocks that may lie ahead. Use it to set up your day from a productivity AND mental / emotional clarity standpoint! 

2. ROMANTICIZE THE HELL out of all the mundane tasks. Whenever I have a boring day of the grind (cardio, meal prep, work, gym, work, class, work, shower, oats) I always tell myself it’s JUST ANOTHER DAY IN PARADISE!! these daily tasks are what build the day to day of your dream life. learn to love them ALL. learn to make a mf movie out of the daily grind. 

3. Schedule in time to relax. I work hard as f*ck but you WILL catch my ass on my couch watching netflix with my beloved protein oats every single night. Also love planning girls nights every couple weeks so I have something to look forward to!!! You can’t pour from an empty cuppppp boo. 

There’s definitely more but these would be my top 3 tips. It can incredibly overwhelming to have so much going on but when you plan accordingly and get yourself in the right headspace for doing it all then it WILL be the most fulfilling & rewarding thing ever.

All too often we think of time as an obstacle to overcome when achieving our goals. 

“It will take too long” 

We hear time and time again that the time is gonna pass by regardless. 

Because it will. 

And after 3 months, 6 months, or in this case 13 months, you can either be closer to your goals or further away. 

But let me offer another reframe. 

We’ve accepted that time is a requirement for a lot of the things we want to achieve. 

We’ve accepted that “it just takes time” 

Instead of viewing that negatively, why don’t we try to frame it as the universe doing us a huge favor; the universe taking something off our plate. 

Let me explain: 

You worry about your nutrition, your workouts, your sleep, your nonnegotiables, your mental health, your macros, your PRs… you worry about ticking off the daily boxes. 

And the universe takes care of time. 

You don’t have to worry about making time pass. About it temporally progressing. 

Instead you focus on everything else and the universe does you a solid by taking this one (very important) thing off your plate. 

I feel like if we think about it that way, we can view the time needed as a gift and not a burden, not an obstacle, not a deterrent. 

Just like reaching your fitness goals requires working out so you workout. 

Or acing your test requires studying so you study. 

All goals require time— but instead of taking that on yourself you can outsource that labor to the ✨universe✨ (or God or Allah or Ganesha or Yeezus or whoever you deem responsible for such a phenomenon!!) 

ALL of that is to say: sometimes a simple reframe can help you overcome what appears to be a huge barrier to entry for most people hesitant about just f*cking STARTING their goals. 

Anyways I’ll leave you to contemplate the metaphysicality of the universe now in peace.

Overcoming bad body image days: 

On Friday I took some BTS of my photoshoot and later caught some glimpses of my ~ lower back fat ~ (forever my arch nemesis!!!) in some rather unflattering angles and immediately tried to ignore it. 

Later that night I swear it was EATING me up. I couldn’t sleep and I was filled w panic anxiety of how tf I could get it removed and was thinking how much worse they’ve gotten over the years and was jst freaking out and was mentally planning some kind of consultation timeline in relation to prep timelines etc etc. I’m not kidding I was in full height of the panic.

when I finally woke up I forced myself to go immediately and take pics of my backside and jst try to prove to myself that it’s not that bad. I told myself to take objective pics and if I still hated them them then we could continue spiraling. 

These are the pics I took. 

I’m ngl. My brain HYPERfocuses on my ~ lower back ~ but when I train my eyes to look at the whole pic I’m actually yeeted as fuck. 

We neeeeeeddd to remember that when you catch pictures of yourself in your worst angles… you are not your 2D worst angle. Just like you are (unfortunately) not your 2D best angle. You are a 3D livin breathin whole ass human being that exists in so many different forms and angles somewhere in between the two and it’s up to YOU to shift your perception of what you wanna focus on!!! 

I get asked ALL the time how I overcome bad body image days and I stg half my confidence comes from gaslighting myself into seeing myself as the hottest piece of ass on this planet LMAOOOO but hey… perception is reality 💅💅

So honestly when it comes to overcoming bad body image what’s worked the most for me is to jst be delulu 💅💅💅

So go take pictures of yourself and train your perception and live your life in your bubble where you are THE shit. Bc the only thing that matters is that YOU see YOURSELF that way‼️‼️

I lived EVERY day in fear of gaining weight. 

Growing up overweight and undergoing a weight loss journey early on, I clung on to the notion that leaner was always better. 

I prepped year after year, initiating a prep whenever I felt “fluffy”. 

I did 12 shows from 2017 to 2020 (pics on left are 2020) and oscillated between varying degrees of shredded.

I always thought other women looked incredible in their curves but simply believed, and I QUOTE, “but in terms of ME i jst prefer a lean hard physique EVEN if it’s objectively less attractive to others.” 

It was never the idea of being thiccer or softer that I was against, it was the idea of ME being thiccer or softer that I was viscerally averse to. 

And I HAVE to believe it’s some weird PTSD from my Blueberry Val days (yes I had blue hair and they called me blueberry). 

Anyways. The irony of it all was that during those years of clinging on to the shreds, my number one goal was (and still is) to be an IFBB Pro. 

But I was getting in my own way of achieving that year after year after year. 

It was only recently in the past few years that I started to break past those limiting beliefs. 

I mean truly if you told 2020 val she would be FORTY pounds heavier…. She would have a full blown panic attack. 

Like truly I was the most thicc-averse human I have ever met to this day and anyone close to me can corroborate that claim. 

But we’re here now. It took some time. And a lot of weight. And a lot of guidance. And a lot of venting to my friends. And a lot of channeling insecurities. And a lot of taking it out on the weights. And a lot of focus. And a lot of positive self talk. And a lot of transparency. And a lot of growth. And a lot of just keep showing up. And a lot of we can do hard things. 

But we’re here now. 

And I’m so happy happy to be here ❤️‍🔥

2 years ago I reached out to @pescience and asked why we didn’t have a fast-assimilating intra workout carb, ideally a Highly-Branched Cyclic Dextrin (HBCD) based one that would benefit resistance training.

Josh responded and was open to what benefits this supplement could provide, and what an ideal formulation would be. 

So I sent over all the research & ideal dosing and after some back & forth and 2 YEARS LATER… 

🤩MY BABY IS HERE🤩

Introse is literally everything I could ever want from an intra-workout carb… which my 1:1 girlies know that I WILL DIE ON THE INTRA CARB HILL FOR OPTIMIZING NUTRIENT PARTITIONING 😤

While there isn’t a TON of research on HBCD, current studies suggest that because it is such a low-osmolality molecule it yields: 
- Increased rates of gastric emptying 
- Faster assimilation 
- Increased rates of glucose uptake into muscle 
- Increased glycogen resynthesis rates (‼️) 

All of which can theoretically (again, confirmatory studies are needed) 
- increase insulin spike & consequent Glut4 translocation 
- Hyperhydrate muscles (an anabolic stimulus in of itself) 
- Super-saturate intra-muscular glycogen (which studies show are the preferred glucose balance of hypertrophying muscles) 

All that being said, there is not a study out there that proves: HBCD will make you bigger. 

BUT I stand by the current body of evidence in showing a really promising potential for this supplement and at the very LEAST I stand by the benefits of partitioning a % of your daily carbohydrates intake to the intra-workout window. 

We formulated Introse to have:
- 15g HBCD 
- 50mg Calcium 
- 50mg Magnesium
- 99mg Potassium
- 50mg Sodium

CHEERS TO 200 DAYS BINGE FREE 🥹🤭🥳

The past 6 months have been… freeing. 

I have made more positive memories in the past 6 months than I think I’ve made in my entire life combined. 

Previously- social events, outings, dinners, parties, any deviation from my routine came with the anxiety that I’d be yielding control…. 

And with the lack of total control usually came a loss of control with food specifically. 

I basically lived every day in fear of a binge lurking around the corner. 

Because it felt like I couldn’t control when they’d occur and it felt like it was always just a matter of time before the next one. 

So with every social plan I made, it came with battle in my head of whether I should be putting myself in a vulnerable situation. It felt like if I gave up total control, I was WELCOMING a binge. 

I have a whole video on what I think changed this time around so I won’t get into that here. 

Instead, I just want to honor all the memories and moments I’ve experienced that I would’ve run away from before. 

This is like 1% of the my favorite moments from the past 200 days. 

don’t get me wrong. A HUGE part of this whole milestone has been my ability to execute the plan to a T on most days… 

It has resulted in the balance I’ve always dreamed of tbh. 

& sometimes even talking about it makes me feel like I’m jinxing it. Because it’s not like !!im cured!! 

It requires DAILY effort to maintain this headspace. 

Daily journaling. Daily reflecting. Daily accountability.

But it’s brought me daily happiness & daily peace that I have NEVER felt before. 

So here’s to my next milestone: 365 days of food freedom. 🫶

6 months of recomping while increasing food and focusing on GROWING. 

Started at 129lbs, reversed down to 119lbs while increasing food, and eventually steadily climbed to 130lbs as we kept pushing food and pulling down cardio. 

So I’m currently heavier than where I started (or have ever been lol) but I’m:
- eating more (the most I ever have in my life) 
- doing less cardio
- lifting heavier and more intentionally
- have better shape & density
- weekly free meals
- HAPPIER!!!! god I’m so much fkn happier lol

& the best part of it is that I’m truly in the BEST place with body image and relationship with food and training and social life and my relationship w myself. ❤️

I think I always knew everything I wanted to achieve was on the other side of a LONG phase of getting my food systematically higher and not doing obnoxious amounts of cardio for once but fear ALWAYS stood in the way of me actually committing to that. 

And 6 months ago I got fed up with my acute intense periods of grinding and falling off and decided to finally do the Hard Thing: 

Ignoring my short term discomforts in the name of my long term goals. 

&& the irony is that by ignoring my short term / present discomforts, I actually grew exponentially more comfortable in the present. 

ESPECIALLY bc every day in the present comes with the knowledge that nothing I’m doing now is compromising my long term goals. 

Anywho. This is the current physique update somewhere towards the end of my offseason. 

Could not be happier tbh. 

So this is your friendly reminder that WE CAN DO HARD THINGS!!!!! & that they’re so fucking worth it.
